<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Wentzel, Willard Ferdinand. A Continuation of the Journal of the Forks Mackenzie's River for Summer 1807-1808. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0022</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p></p>
<p class="head">December Continued 1807</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Monday 22<sup>nd</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Sent off the before mentioned Indians<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Sent word to those who are well not to concern themselves about the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Chien</span> <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Brule's</span> disorder that I would let his by<sup>r</sup> my Hare Hunter take particular care of him during the time <span class="DelHand-author">she</span> of his illness<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The men busy white washing the inside of the House<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p>Tues<sup>y</sup> 23<sup>rd</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The men Cleaning the House &amp; washing the Floorings<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Very Cold weather<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p>Wednes<sup>y</sup> 24<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Only a little Snow <span style="text-decoration:underline;">occurred</span> to day<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p>Thurs<sup>y</sup> 25<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  This being Christmas I gave each of the men a Dram of Shrub<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Friday 26<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Croup de Chien who had went to try his Skill as a phycian upon the Chien Brulé returned to day &#8211; saying that he was past Curre<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[A]</span>fter this Oration he set off to visit his <span class="AddHand-author">Snares</span> being almost famished &#8211; where if he finds any Hares, he will display his abilities <span class="AddHand-author">to</span> better effect In Cracking his <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Chops</span><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Gaucher</span> the other Hunter remains to be an eye witness of the issue of his Sick Brothers indisposition<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Satur<sup>y</sup> 27<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Arrived an Indian who I have not seen Since the Fall &#8211; paid his debts to the Amount Four Skins and Traded 14 in B<sup>r</sup> &amp; 4 B<sup>r</sup> Tails<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[H]</span>e gave me no information respecting any others of his Tribe &#8211; being alone (three days march from this) with his mother &amp; a <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Blind</span> By<sup>r</sup> inlaw<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Middling Fine weather<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p>Sunday 28<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Sent off the Stranger who arrived yester<sup>y</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p>Mon<sup>y</sup> 29<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Tues<sup>y</sup> 30<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  And that's All<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Wed<sup>y</sup> 31<sup>st</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Gave a Beaver in meat &#8211; 7 white Fish &amp; 6 Hares to the men to arrange a <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Fricos</span> for tomorrow's entertain<sup>t</sup>, got besides these a great number of <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Cakes</span> made &#8211; a mixture of Flour &amp; <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Fishs row</span><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Spent Grease 2½<sup>lb</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Tolerable weather<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Thurs<sup>y</sup> January 1<sup>st</sup> 1808<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Did not allow the men to Fire at my windows as usual, my Hunters would have heard &amp; thus created an additional expence by hastening to the Summons<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Spent in Drams &amp;<sup>c</sup> &amp;<sup>c</sup> 1 Quart HWines &amp; ¾ of a Flaggen Shrub &#8211; and 1 Fm Twist Tob<sup>o</sup> &#8211; agreeable to former Customs<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  In the afternoon Capot Rouge arrived brought with a Scullion of his 36 B<sup>rs</sup> &amp; 2 in Prov<sup>ns</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Gaucher also came to tell me that his by<sup>r</sup> was yet dying for tho' he Should have but a Sore <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Toe</span> he is sure to belong to the Dead &#8211; &amp; therefore cannot leave him untill he has either recovered or goes off entirely<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Spent a Quart of mixt rum to these fellows &amp; 1½ foot Tob<sup>o</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Capot Rouge Says that he</p>
